^-|CP||ht|l|AT|^c@2^Y@3^*BAfter an opponent's preempt things can get rather sticky. Once you are forced to guess, even the world's best players sometimes will not get to their best contract. However, knowing what to do after an enemy preempt does not need to be a blind guess. The key is to be able to answer the age old critical question "to bid or not to bid?".

How can you know the answer? It is a combination of exercising good judgment and relying on some important principles. That is what this lesson is all about.

Your RHO opens 2@H and you have this @S A 6 @H 7 6 @D A K Q 8 6 5 @C A K 2 hand. What is the expert bid here? 

There are expert bids that you are capable of making. Most experts would cue bid 3@H. We don't use Michaels cue bids when the opponents open a weak 2-bid in a major. We find it is more useful to cue bid to show a terrific hand with a long strong minor but without a stopper in their suit. We are begging partner to bid 3NT with a stopper. If partner does not have a stopper, he does the best he can.

Bergen/Howard recent audio visual lessons "How To Survive An Enemy Preempt" |CP|1|AT|^*Htiny.cc/596kdx^*N|CP||
